post_text:
UPDATE: The Board Study Session scheduled for Wednesday, September 9, 2020 at 6:00 pm was originally scheduled to take place at Steilacoom High School. However, the legislative leadership extended the statutory waivers/suspensions of the Open Public Meeting Act (OPMA) cited in Proclamation 20-28.4 until 11:59 p.m. October 1, 2020. Based on this extension, meetings that are open to the public must be held remotely. The September 9 Study Session will be held via a Zoom webinar.

No decision making is undertaken at a Study Session, and Study Sessions do not offer a Public Comments section. All viewers will be placed on mute for the meeting.

Zoom info can be found on our website here: https://www.steilacoom.k12.wa.us/Page/1092

SHSD is excited to announce its Family Academy. Our first sessions start on September 8.

The Family Academy is a series of interactive sessions designed to help families and caring adults support their student learners. We are all in this together and a strong connection and collaboration between the school and the family support system is critical. We are limiting the size of each session to ensure families can interact with our session facilitators - but resources provided in each session will also be available on our website for all families. We look forward to seeing you!

Click here for our Family Academy schedule, and to register for a session. https://www.steilacoom.k12.wa.us/Page/8938

Some ways to strengthen emotional intelligence include normalizing talking about emotions, really listening to each other, keeping an "emotions diary," and setting and keeping routines like family meal time, walks, or evening check-ins to help family members feel connected and increase trust. #SELTogether

post_text: This school year will bring new challenges, as we experience many things we have never had to navigate in the past. The skills and competencies encompassed by Social Emotional Learning are essential at all times, but SEL’s importance has become even more clear with the challenges related to COVID-19. Our district vision remains the same; the Best Education for Every Student and the investment in Social Emotional Learning is rooted in our sincere belief in every student’s potential. Our school system is committed to ensuring equitable learning environments in which every child can shine!

post_text:
Pandemic EBT (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for children who qualified for free or reduced price school meals when schools were closed last spring. P-EBT provides funds (up to $399 per eligible child) to help low income families buy groceries. It works like a debit card and can be used at any store or farmers markets that accept food stamps (SNAP). Children are eligible for P-EBT regardless of citizenship or immigration status; it is not a public charge for a child or their family if they use P-EBT.

If an eligible family does not already receive food stamps (SNAP), they must complete a simple application to receive P-EBT. Apply via DSHS online (www.WashingtonConnection.org) or by phone (877-501-2233, 8am - 5pm Monday-Friday). P-EBT applications must be completed by Friday, Sept. 11 by 5pm.

post_text:
SHSD families, welcome to ParentSquare!

We are introducing ParentSquare for all school communication, primarily with email, text and app notifications. ParentSquare automatically generates an account for each parent, using their preferred email address and phone number. We encourage parents to access their accounts so they can download the mobile app and update their preferences on when and how they are notified.

Here’s what you can do with ParentSquare:
*Receive messages from the school via email, text or app notification
*Choose to receive information as it comes or all at once at 6pm daily
*Communicate in your preferred language
*Comment on school postings to engage in your school community
*Direct message teachers, staff and other parents
*Participate in group messages
*Complete daily health screening before arriving to campus
*Sign up for parent-teacher conferences with smart online technology
*Sign forms & permission slips, receive report cards, sign up to volunteer and more all from your phone or web portal

SHSD will be hosting two informational webinars on Wednesday, August 19 to provide families and students a better idea of what they can expect when schools reopen.

Our afternoon session will take place from 2:00 - 3:00 pm, and we will also offer an evening session from 6:00 - 7:00 pm. Zoom links can be found on our district website calendar.

Our team will share a reopening plan presentation, and then there will be an opportunity for a community question and answer session. Please review the district's FAQ page on the website prior to the webinar to ensure that questions asked are not already addressed on our FAQ page. We will answer as many questions as possible during the 1-hour webinar, but will also answer any remaining questions via email or phone.

The webinars will be recorded and shared for families unable to attend.

Summer Meal Program Reminder!

SHSD does not normally qualify for a summer meals program, but we were able to receive a waiver for this summer, and will continue serving free meals (lunch and breakfast for following day) from July 1 through August 13 at the following sites:
Cherrydale Primary School - Steilacoom
Pioneer Middle School - DuPont
Chief Leschi Park - DuPont

Grab 'n go meals will be served from 11:30 am to 12:30 pm Monday through Thursday (Friday meals will also be served on Thursday).

All children age 0-18 are eligible to receive the free meals.

post_text:
The last day of SHSD free meal distribution services will be June 30, 2020.

The Steilacoom Historical School District does not sponsor a Summer Meals program. However, there are local resources for children during the summer months while school is not in session.

Contact the USDA Summer Meals Hotline at (866) 348-6479. Families will receive assistance to find the location, meal times, and contact information for summer meals based on their full address, city, and/or zip code.

USDA Summer Meals Finder at www.fns.usda.gov/summerfoodrocks This website is easy for families to use as they can access summer meals locations by entering their zip code.

These resources will be updated throughout the summer. More information can be found here https://www.steilacoom.k12.wa.us/Page/6033

To our senior students, we are so proud of you! Thanks for letting us be a part of your journey.

To our families, thank you for trusting us with your most prized possessions.

To our staff, thanks for sharing your passion with our kids each day.

Specifically, we want to say thank you to Mrs. Stefani James and Mrs. Sarah Campbell for their roles in creating this event. Many hours of work goes into creating a product like this one, and we would not have made it here without them.

One last note, diplomas will be available for pickup at the school beginning June 24.

Sincerely,
Mike, Jake & Katie - SHS Administrative Team
#TheStandard #SteillyPride

post_text: U.S. News and World Report recently named Steilacoom High School to their “Best High School 2020” list. The school also received this honor in 2019. Steilacoom High School is ranked 72nd out of 674 traditional high schools in Washington state. High schools around the national were ranked on six indicators of school quality. The ranking indicators included College Readiness Index, College Curriculum Breadth Index, Math and Reading Proficiency, Math and Reading Performance, and Graduation Rate.

post_text: Chloe Clark Elementary School has received recognition from The State Board of Education (SBE), the Educational Opportunity Gap Oversight and Accountability Committee (EOGOAC), and the Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction (OSPI). The program is called the "Washington School Recognition Program," (formerly the Washington Achievement Awards) and occurs annually. Based on the Washington School Improvement Framework, schools are recognized for work around equitably closing gaps, growth, and achievement. The framework considers multiple measures, including growth, achievement, and student success indicators like attendance and completion of dual credit coursework. Chloe Clark Elementary School was recognized in the category of growth for students who qualify for the free and reduced price lunch program.

From Cherrydale's Ms. Johansen: Notice Dylan standing there with her multiplication timing? This is what happens in the classroom when they pass a timing. We celebrate and students get their picture taken. So, at home, Dylan is continuing to learn her facts and to be tested on them. Although Ms. Bettye Craft is not shown, she is in charge of weekly timings. You can see just how valuable our volunteers are when they instill learning that extends into independence at home.
Way to go, Ms. Johansen, Ms. Craft, and DYLAN (100% with one minute left!). We are so proud of you all for your dedication to learning!

post_text:
REMINDER:

Meals will continue to be distributed during the week of Spring Break. However, due to changing guidance from the CDC and the State of Washington, the following change will be implemented with our community meal program. Beginning Thursday, April 9, we will now be distributing two days’ worth of meals each Thursday. Each Thursday a child will receive two breakfasts and two lunches, to cover both Thursday and Friday. Meal distribution sites will no longer be open on Fridays beginning Friday, April 10. To ensure food safety at home, please refrigerate your meals as soon as possible.

We also ask you to continue to partner with us on maintaining social distancing during meal pick-up. Please be mindful of maintaining a 6 foot distance at all times during the process.

Thank you to our communities for your understanding and cooperation as we continue to navigate these challenging times.

post_text:
This afternoon, Governor Inslee announced that schools will be closed for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year, in order to slow the spread of COVID-19 Coronavirus. During this closure, all schools in the district will remain closed.

We want to reassure our entire student community that public schools have been and will continue to support students and families with nutritional and childcare services, as we have at the very onset of COVID 19. A special thank you to our educators who have provided distance learning opportunities, homework packets, and checked in with students, to stay connected in meaningful ways. In the days and weeks ahead, we will all be working together to try to get answers to your most pressing questions as we navigate through these unprecedented times. Please continue to monitor school and district websites, along with checking email to keep up to date with the most recent changes in information.

post_text:
Spring Break for Steilacoom Historical School District is next week - Monday, April 6 through Friday, April 10. While it seems as if nothing is normal right now, we are honoring this date and asking the majority of our staff members to unplug and embrace this important break. We invite you to do the same with your families.

Our meal service will continue for children during the break, with the new modified schedule going into effect. Meals will be served Monday through Thursday, with two breakfast and two lunch meals being served on Thursday. This will be the new meal distribution schedule, and meal distribution sites will be closed on Fridays beginning April 10.

We look forward to reconnecting virtually with you all on April 13.

post_text: May we humbly suggest that, if you haven't yet, you and your family begin gratitude journals? When life is uncertain, and seems full of disappointments and what we can't do right now, it can be helpful to focus on what we can do and what we do have. It can help give us a new perspective on what is really important to us and help us develop an "attitude of gratitude." Maybe you set aside a time each day where each family member shares their list for the day?

A lot has changed over the last week for our families. The Census Bureau is carefully monitoring the situation and working with national, state, and local health authorities as the 2020 Census is underway. They are adapting their operations where needed, but their goal is still the same – to ensure a complete and accurate count of everyone, including children.

2020 Census invitations are in the mail. Families can respond online, or respond by paper when a form is delivered.

While our district is providing families with excellent learning activities during this school closure, teaching our kiddos about the census is another great activity for families to do together.

post_text:
It’s a census year— be sure that you and your family are counted! Every 10 years, the U.S. Constitution requires a count of everyone living in the country. The info gathered in the Census helps determine how much federal funding goes to our communities to support important services like roads, hospitals and schools.

The 2020 Census is right around the corner. Starting in March, you’ll receive mail from the U.S. Census Bureau asking you to take the census online or by phone. The process is quick and easy, and it helps ensure that Washington is fully counted. Check out 2020census.gov to learn more.

You make us #PublicSchoolProud!

Reminder! DDA Application Night is tonight!

Steilacoom Historical School District and Pierce County Developmental Disabilities Administration (DDA) invite families to a DDA Application Night. District staff will partner with DDA staff to assist families in learning about systems and supports for children and young adults with disabilities. It is suggested that families bring proof of diagnosis and copy of current IEP/Evaluation.View DDA’s Guide to Eligibility Supports and Services.

post_text:
This week is Public Schools Week. Public schools open doors for every child—regardless of zip code. Public schools recognize the importance of social emotional development and provide a safe, nurturing environment where students can become effective, empowered learners.

Today's SHSD focus is Cherrydale Primary School, where 2nd grade teacher, Mrs. Bianca Kirby, uses Socratic seminars and quotes from Notable US heroes in her room to inspire her kids. Mrs. Kirby says that her student, Dante Silver, always shows up to school with a positive attitude and encouraging words to his classmates. When things get hard, he is the first one to say, "Mistakes are proof you're trying!" which is one of the posters that hangs in her room. Way to go, Mrs. Kirby and Dante! You make us #PublicSchoolProud!

post_text:
SHSD received two Lakewood Rotary awards this month!

Congratulations to SHS sophomore Shayla McKenzie, who received the Lakewood Rotary Outstanding Student of the Month Award. Shayla is a two-sport athlete, carries a 3.98 GPA, and is an active member of the yearbook staff. Most importantly, Shayla is a kind student who models excellent behavior and Steily PRIDE every day!

And, congratulations to Anderson Island Elementary teacher Janet Friedlos, who received the Lakewood Rotary Outstanding Educator of the Month award. Janet was recognized for being a relationship-builder, motivator, and advocate. She has a true passion for her students, helping them learn not only basic curriculum, but encouraging them to delve deeper and ask questions about why or how something works the way it does.

Congratulations, Shayla and Janet!

post_text:
Congrats to SHS senior Karenna Merritt, who received a shout-out in Pierce County's Environmental Education Newsletter.

"As the Environmental Club President, she is leading her school's efforts in becoming a Washington Green School with a campaign to combat idling and encourage carpooling. In addition to her role at school, Karenna volunteers to help plan the YESS (Pierce County Youth Sustainability and Environmental Summit).
Not only is she passionate about doing good for the planet, she is artistic! It is her artwork that inspired this year’s summit logo! We thank Karenna for her leadership and dedication and can’t wait to see what she does in the future."

Steilacoom Historical School District will be hosting two public screenings of the documentary film Screenagers Next Chapter. The screenings will be held Thursday, February 27 at 6:30 pm at Pioneer Middle School in DuPont and Tuesday, March 3 at 6:30 pm at Steilacoom High School in Steilacoom. A panel of local mental health experts will answer questions and facilitate discussion following the Pioneer Middle School screening on February 27.

post_text: February's SEL focus is myelin. As myelin grows, it speeds up the signals along the brain's neural pathways. TIP: We all need lots of practice to turn new skills into an automatic and permanent habit. Myelin grows little by little each time we practice. Practice translates to real physical changes, ultimately making you more efficient.

post_text:
From the City of DuPont:

PSE is installing a utility pipe from Station Drive to DuPont-Steilacoom Road and completed through the Barksdale Avenue intersection to Historic Village.

This project will be in multiple phases. The project will start on February 10th and stop on March 6th 2020. This contractor will have to return in the Spring of 2020 to finalize pavement. Attached table provides schedule details.

This project will have one lane open daily and temporary lane closures with flaggers. This project will have detours entering Historic Village via Haskell Street emergency vehicle access when work is occurring in the Barksdale Intersection, March 2nd to 6th. This work will be during the day from 8:00 AM to 3:00 PM. A portion of Station Drive will be performed at night from 6:00 PM to 5:00 AM.

The roads will be covered with steel plates and opened nightly.

post_text: Our SEL calendar for January focuses on Metacognition, which is the knowledge and regulation of one's own thinking process. When we have strong metacognitive skills, we are able to anticipate change and navigate complex situations. TIP: Guide children to ask themselves questions like: How did my mindset affect how I did my work? How can my study environment be improved? How can I best use my strengths to learn?

post_text:
Pioneer Middle School STEM challenges!

6th Grade STEM Challenge: Design and create a tower taller than 1 meter using 3 sheets of paper, 3 straws, and tape to test for structure, strength, and durability.

7th Grade Engineering STEM Challenge: Design and create models of storm surge barriers and test them using a "hurricane force wind" shop vac. The students also designed, tested, and made revisions of models of the Hydrologic Cycle to demonstrate the transfer of heat energy.

8th Grade STEM Challenge: Discover the physical properties of unknown substances working in lab teams and communicate findings with the class.

post_text: Our district's SEL calendar for December brings us executive function, which is often referred to as the CEO of the brain and helps us pay attention, organize, plan, and prioritize. Tip: Picture schedules can help younger children get organized and complete tasks. Families can help older children set goals and prioritize activities.

post_text: Our Steilacoom Sentinels football team continued to make history on Saturday with their decisive 42-0 victory over the Lynden Lions! Next stop is the WIAA 2A State Championship game on Saturday, December 7 at Sparks Stadium @ 4:00 pm. Let's pack the stadium to show our support of these amazing student athletes!
